    <Backlink />
    <p class="eyebrow">(An Appendix of Terms)</p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        A quick reference for the terms used throughout <a
          href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a
        >. Each entry points back to the chapter where it is taught in full —
        follow it there for the complete treatment.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <hr />
    <h2>Glossary</h2>
    <p>
      <strong>Severed Story.</strong> This game — a handbook of life and joyful labor
      on a Lumon severed floor, and the rules for playing it. See the
      <a href="/preamble">Preamble</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Boon.</strong> A standing benefit earned upon reaching a new Tier in
      a row. See
      <a href="/performance-evaluation">Performance Evaluation</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Burnout.</strong> What befalls an employee whose stress fills every
      box. Burnout earns a Demerit. See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Confidence.</strong> A favorable Roll: throw 2d20 and take the
      <em>higher</em>
      die. Granted when a Roll falls under one of an employee&#x27;s Core Competencies.
      See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Core Competency.</strong> A Core Principle an employee is especially
      practiced in, marked on the LIEP. Rolls made under it are made with Confidence.
      See
      <a href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Core Principle.</strong> One of the Nine practiced virtues of Lumon.
      Every Roll is made under the Principle that best embodies the action. See
      <a href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Corporate Persona.</strong> An archetype assigned by the LIEP that shapes
      an employee&#x27;s Temper Points and grants Special Attributes. See
      <a href="/corporate-personas">Corporate Personas</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>d20.</strong> The twenty-sided die. The heart of every Roll. See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Demerit.</strong> A formal mark against an employee. Three Demerits
      bring Termination. See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Departmental Standing.</strong> A department&#x27;s collective reputation,
      which rises and falls with the conduct of all its members. See
      <a href="/classified">Classified</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>The Four Tempers.</strong> Frolic, Malice, Woe, and Dread — the four
      dispositions of the soul. Each Core Principle answers to, and tames, a parent
      Temper. See
      <a href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>GM.</strong> Your General Manager, who narrates the floor, sets each
      Task Severity, and adjudicates every Roll. (Some tables read the letters differently.
      Both readings are correct.) See
      <a href="/table-of-contents">Severed Story</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Hesitance.</strong> An unfavorable Roll: throw 2d20 and take the
      <em>lower</em>
      die. Imposed by mounting stress and other burdens. See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Kier Point.</strong> A point earned for service to Lumon, recorded in
      a Temper row and summed toward that row&#x27;s rolls. See
      <a href="/performance-evaluation">Performance Evaluation</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>LIEP.</strong> The Lumon Industries Employee Profile — the document
      that records who an employee is, and the sheet you play from. See
      <a href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Modifier.</strong> Any number added to a Roll before it is compared
      to Task Severity — chiefly Temper Points and Kier Points. See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
