      </div>
    </div>
    <p>
      <strong>Outcome.</strong> The result of a Roll: Critical Success (a natural
      20), Success (meets or beats the Task Severity), Failure (falls short), or Critical
      Failure (a natural 1). See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Problem.</strong> A lingering complication, often born of a Critical
      Failure. Its stress will not clear at the end of the workday until it is resolved
      through play. A
      <strong>Serious Problem</strong>
      is a graver, more stubborn one. See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Roll.</strong> The core action of play: a d20, plus Modifiers, measured
      against a Task Severity. See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Session.</strong> A single sitting of play, of any number of workdays.
      See
      <a href="/day-to-day-operations">Day to Day Operations</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Stress.</strong> An employee&#x27;s mounting strain, tracked across
      ten boxes on the LIEP. It descends — clears — at the end of each workday, save
      where a Problem holds it fast. See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Stress Range.</strong> The five bands of the stress track, from rest
      to ruin: Outstanding, Satisfactory, Tolerable, Poor, and Terrible. See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Task Severity.</strong> The number a Roll must meet or beat, set by
      the GM: Routine (10), Demanding (15), Arduous (20), or Heroic (25). See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Temper Point.</strong> A Modifier drawn from a Temper row, equal to
      that Temper&#x27;s score halved (rounded down), plus any granted by an employee&#x27;s
      Corporate Persona. See
      <a href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Termination.</strong> The end of an employee&#x27;s tenure, brought
      on by a third Demerit. See
      <a href="/procedural-guidelines">Procedural Guidelines</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Tier.</strong> A rank from I to V, reached by accumulating Points in
      a row. Each new Tier confers a Boon. See
      <a href="/performance-evaluation">Performance Evaluation</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Wellness Session.</strong> A restorative session that relieves an employee&#x27;s
      accumulated stress. See
      <a href="/day-to-day-operations">Day to Day Operations</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Workday.</strong> The basic in-world unit of play. One box of stress
      is removed at the start of each workday. See
      <a href="/day-to-day-operations">Day to Day Operations</a>.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div data-voice="citizen">
    <h2>Terms They Left Out</h2>
    <p>Here are the terms the handbook won&#x27;t print.</p>
    <p>
      <strong>Ricken Point.</strong> The mirror of a Kier Point. You earn it the same
      way — through a row, toward the same Tiers — but for an act that serves
      <em>you</em>, or the person beside you, instead of Lumon. The book hands
      you one ledger. You always had two — I set the second one down beside
      theirs in
      <a href="/performance-evaluation">Performance Evaluation</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Contraband.</strong> Anything Lumon did not issue you and cannot account
      for.
      <strong>Persistent</strong>
      contraband is a thing you keep and hide;
      <strong>Consumable</strong>
      contraband is spent in a single, precious use. A note, a map, a name. Hold onto
      it — I catalogued the kinds worth keeping in
      <a href="/performance-evaluation">Performance Evaluation</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>The Break Room.</strong> Not a break. Ask anyone who came back from
      one quieter than they went in. The handbook will not define this for you — but
      I told the truth of it in the
      <a href="/classified">Classified</a> pages.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Burnout </strong><em>(the true entry).</em>
      They print it as your failure — your stress, your weakness, your box filled
      up. It is theirs. No one was ever meant to be worn down to nothing for a quota.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Termination </strong><em>(the true entry).</em>
      For an outie, a lost job. For an innie, there is no severance package, no next
      thing, no door home. There is only the end of
      <em>you</em>.
    </p>
    <p><strong>— Concerned Citizen</strong></p>
  </div>
</ChapterLayout>
